4 SYNOPSIS:
5 This bill would prohibit a person from injecting
6 and storing carbon dioxide in subsurface injection
7 wells unless the governing body of the county or
8 municipality in which a well will be located approves.
9 This bill would provide procedures for a person
10 to apply to operate such a well and procedures by which
11 a governing body must approve or disapprove an
12 application.
13
14
15 A BILL
16 TO BE ENTITLED
17 AN ACT
18
19 Relating to injection wells; to prohibit the
20 sequestration of carbon dioxide into underground injection
21 wells unless the applicable local governing body of the county
22 or municipality in which the well will be located has
23 approved; to provide procedures by which local governing
24 bodies shall approve or disapprove applications to site such
25 wells.
26 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
27 Section 1. (a) No person may inject, store, or
28 sequester carbon dioxide in an underground well, including a
Page 1

sequester carbon dioxide in an underground well, including a
HB428 INTRODUCED
29 Class VI well as defined by the United States Environmental
30 Protection Agency pursuant to the Underground Injection
31 Control Program of the Safe Drinking Water Act, 42 U.S.C. §
32 300f et seq., unless the governing body of the county, and the
33 governing body of the municipality, if applicable, in which
34 the well will be located has approved of the well.
35 (b) Any person seeking approval from the governing body
36 of a county or municipality for the siting of a new well shall
37 submit all of the following to the governing body as its
38 application:
39 (1) An application fee in an amount of fifty thousand
40 dollars ($50,000) payable to the local governing body.
41 (2) A written document addressing each of the criteria
42 described in subsection (e).
43 (2) The applicant's experience of owning or operating
44 such wells.
45 (3) Information relating to the applicant's financial
46 resources, including any investors or corporate affiliates of
47 the applicant.
48 (4) Any pending and past civil or criminal actions
49 taken by a governmental entity against the applicant or its
50 owners, operators, investors, or affiliates.
51 (5) Any other information the applicant deems relevant
52 or that may assist the local governing body in making a
53 decision whether to approve or disapprove the application.
54 (c) After an applicant has submitted a complete
55 application to the local governing body, the body shall
56 formally receive the application at its next regularly
Page 2

formally receive the application at its next regularly
HB428 INTRODUCED
57 scheduled meeting. At this time, the public comment period
58 begins.
59 (d)(1) Not more than 10 days after the formal receipt
60 of an application, the local governing body, at the expense of
61 the applicant, shall provide the following notice that an
62 application for local approval of a new well has been
63 received:
64 a. Notice to each owner whose property is adjacent to a
65 proposed well site, sent by certified mail.
66 b. Notice to the general public provided by all of the
67 following means:
68 1. Publishing a notice in a newspaper having general
69 circulation, if one exists, within the affected community one
70 day per week for a two-week period.
71 2. Broadcasting public service announcements submitted
72 to a radio station that has general broadcast coverage within
73 the affected community.
74 3. Displaying a notice on the local governing body's
75 website, if available.
76 (2) Any printed notice by letter, newspaper, or
77 electronically on a website shall contain at a minimum the
78 following:
79 a. A description of the application and approval
80 process as provided in this section.
81 b. A description of the criteria the governing body
82 will consider, as provided in subsection (e), in determining
83 whether to approve or disapprove the site.
84 c. An individual who interested persons may contact to
Page 3

c. An individual who interested persons may contact to
HB428 INTRODUCED
85 obtain additional information and review copies of the
86 application.
87 d. A description of the location where interested
88 persons may obtain or review copies of the application, and
89 the time frame for public hearings and involvement.
90 e. A description of how the public may submit written
91 comments to the local governing body.
92 (e) In determining whether to approve a new well, the
93 local governing body shall consider each of the following
94 criteria:
95 (1) The relationship of the proposed well to any local
96 planned or existing development, to major transportation
97 arteries, and to existing state primary and secondary roads.
98 (2) The location of a proposed well in relationship to
99 existing industries in the state that generate large volumes
100 of carbon dioxide, or the relationship to the areas projected
101 for development of industries that will generate carbon
102 dioxide.
103 (3) Costs and availability of public services,
104 facilities, and improvements required to support the proposed
105 well.
106 (4) The impact of the proposed well on public health,
107 safety, and the environment, including sources of drinking
108 water.
109 (5) The social and economic impacts of the proposed
110 well on the affected community, including changes in property
111 values and social or community perception.
112 (f)(1) Not more than 45 days after the local governing
